'''Herbert Ihlefeld''' (1 June 1914&nbsp;– 8 August 1995) was a German ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' [[military aviation|military aviator]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]] and [[World War II]], a [[fighter ace]] listed with 130 enemy aircraft shot down in over 1,000 combat missions. He claimed seven victories in the Spanish Civil War, and during World War II, 67 on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] and 56 on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]], including 15 [[Heavy bomber|four-engined bombers]] and 26 [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s. He survived being shot down eight times during his 1,000 combat missions.{{sfn|Spick|2006|pp=231–232}}

Born in [[Pniewo, Złotów County|Pinnow]], Ihlefeld volunteered for military service in the ''[[Reichswehr]]'' of [[Nazi Germany]] in 1933.{{refn|From 1919, Germany's national defense force was known as the ''Reichswehr''. That name was dropped in favor of ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' on 16 March 1935.<ref>{{Cite web |work= |title=Proklamation der Reichsregierung an das deutsche Volk bezüglich der Einführung der allgemeinen Wehrpflicht |trans-title=Proclamation of the German Government to the German people regarding the introduction of compulsory military service |url=http://www.documentarchiv.de/ns/1935/allgemein-wehrpflicht-einfuehrung_prokl.html |language=German |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>|group="Note"}} Initially serving in the ''[[German Army (Wehrmacht)|Heer]]'' (Army), he transferred to the ''Luftwaffe'' (Air Force) in 1935. Following flight training, he volunteered for service with the [[Condor Legion]] during the Spanish Civil War where he was assigned to [[Jagdgruppe 88|''Jagdgruppe'' 88]] (J/88—88th Fighter Group). From February–July 1938, he claimed nine aerial victories, two remained unconfirmed. For his service in Spain he was awarded the [[Spanish Cross]] in Gold with Swords.

Following service in Spain, Ihlefeld was posted to [[Lehrgeschwader 2|''Lehrgeschwader'' 2]] (LG&nbsp;2—2nd Demonstration Wing. With this unit he participated in the [[Invasion of Poland]] and [[Battle of France]]. During the height of the [[Battle of Britain]] on 13 September 1940, he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] after 21 aerial victories in World War II. Ihlefeld, who had been appointed ''[[Gruppenkommandeur]]'' (group commander) of I. ''Gruppe'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 77|''Jagdgeschwader'' 77]] (JG&nbsp;77—77th Fighter Wing) in September 1940, fought in the aerial battles of the [[Balkan Campaign (World War II)|Balkan Campaign]]. During [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of the Soviet Union, he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]] on 27 June 1941. Ten months later, following his 101st aerial victory of the war, Ihlefeld was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]] on 24 April 1942.

On 22 June 1942, Ihlefeld was appointed ''[[Geschwaderkommodore]]'' (wing commander) of [[Jagdgeschwader 52|''Jagdgeschwader'' 52]] (JG&nbsp;52—52nd Fighter Wing). He was injured in combat on 22 July 1942 and after convalescence, he was given command of [[Jagdfliegerschule|''Jagdfliegerschule'' 3]] (3rd Fighter Pilot School). On 21 July 1943, he was tasked with leadership of a high flying [[de Havilland Mosquito]] intercept unit called [[Jagdgeschwader 25|''Jagdgeschwader'' 25]] (JG&nbsp;25—25th Fighter Wing) in [[Defense of the Reich]]. This unit failed to achieve its objective and Ihlefeld was assigned to the ''[[Stab (Luftwaffe designation)|Stab]]'' (headquarters unit) of the [[30th Fighter Division (Germany)|30th Fighter Division]]. On 20 May 1944, he took command of [[Jagdgeschwader 1 (World War II)|''Jagdgeschwader'' 1]] "Oesau" (JG&nbsp; 1—1st Fighter Wing) and participated in [[Operation Bodenplatte]]. Ihlefeld died on 8 August 1995 in [[Wennigsen]], [[Lower Saxony]].

==Early life and career==
Ihlefeld was born on 1 June 1914 in [[Pniewo, Złotów County|Pinnow]], at the time in the [[Province of Pomerania (1815–1945)|Province of Pomerania]], a [[Provinces of Prussia|province]] of the [[Kingdom of Prussia]], the son of a farm laborer. Following a [[machinist]] [[vocational education]], he volunteered for military service in the ''[[Reichsheer]]'' on 1 April 1933. As a ''[[Grenadier]]'', he was first posted to ''Infanterie-Regiment'' 5 (5th Infantry Regiment) based in [[Stettin]] and in 1934 was posted to the aviation technical school at [[Jüterbog]].{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}} In March 1937, he was assigned to the I. ''[[Organization of the Luftwaffe (1933–45)#Gruppe|Gruppe]]'' (1st group) of [[Jagdgeschwader 132|''Jagdgeschwader'' 132]] "Richthofen" (JG&nbsp;32—132nd Fighter Wing).{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=31}}<ref group="Note">For an explanation of ''Luftwaffe'' unit designations see [[Organization of the Luftwaffe (1933–45)|Organization of the ''Luftwaffe'' during World War II]].</ref>

[[File:Legion-Condor-Badge-2nd-Squadron-Fighter-Group-88.jpg|thumb|right|2. ''Staffel'' insignia]]
With outbreak of the [[Spanish Civil War]] in July 1936, Germany supported the [[National faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalists]] and asked for volunteers which organized in the [[Condor Legion]] ({{lang|de|Legion Condor}}). ''[[Unteroffizier]]'' (Staff Sergeant) Ihlefeld joined 2. ''[[Organization of the Luftwaffe (1933–45)#Staffel|Staffel]]'' (2nd squadron) of [[Jagdgruppe 88|''Jagdgruppe'' 88]] (J/88—88th Fighter Group) in late 1937. Flying with this unit until July 1938, he claimed nine and was credited with seven aerial victories over Spain and was awarded the [[Spanish Cross|Spanish Cross in Gold with Swords]] (''Spanienkreuz in Gold mit Schwertern''). There, he was issued one of the first [[Messerschmitt Bf 109 variants#Bf 109 A/B/C/D|Messerschmitt Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;B-1]]'s sent to the Condor Legion.{{sfn|Jackson|2015|p=48}} A [[Polikarpov I-16]] fighter aircraft shot down on 21 February 1938 was his first aerial victory of the war.{{sfn|Forsyth|2011|p=90}} On 13 March 1938, Ihlefeld was credited with his second victory, a [[Polikarpov I-15]] biplane fighter aircraft followed by his third, a I-16, on 11 May 1938. A week later, on 18 May, he claimed another I-16, the victory was unconfirmed. A [[Tupolev SB|Tupolev SB-2]] bomber from a force attacking [[La Sénia]], shot down on 2 June 1938, became his fifth victim.{{sfn|Forsyth|2011|p=94}} He claimed another unconfirmed victory on 25 June 1938 over a I-16. On 12 July 1938, he was credited with a victory over a I-15. Two I-15s shot down on 15 July 1938 were his last victories in Spain.{{sfn|Forsyth|2011|p=103}}

On 1 August 1938, he was assigned to I. (''[[Jagdwaffe|Jäger]]'') ''Gruppe'' (1st fighter group) of [[Lehrgeschwader 2|''Lehrgeschwader'' 2]] (LG&nbsp;2—2nd Demonstration Wing), an operational training unit tasked with the evaluation of new types of aircraft and tactics. The unit was later redesignated to I. ''Gruppe'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 77|''Jagdgeschwader'' 77]] (JG&nbsp;77—77th Fighter Wing). On 20 August 1938, he was promoted to ''[[Leutnant]]'' (second lieutenant).{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}}

==World War II==
World War II in Europe began on Friday, 1 September 1939, when German forces [[Invasion of Poland|invaded Poland]]. Ihlefeld flew his first [[Military operation|combat missions]] over Poland and was awarded the [[Iron Cross]] 2nd Class ({{lang|de|Eisernes Kreuz zweiter Klasse}}) on 26 September 1939.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}} On 10 May 1940, the [[Battle of France]], the German invasion of France and the [[Low Countries]], began and Ihlefeld claimed his first victory of the war on 29 May 1940.{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=31}} The combat took place at an altitude of {{convert|2500|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} near [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint-Quentin]] during the [[Battle of Dunkirk]] (26 May&nbsp;– 4 June 1940), the defense and evacuation of British and allied forces from France to England, on a [[combat air patrol]]. On this mission, 11 [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]s encountered two ''[[French Air Force|Armée de l'air]]'' (French Air Force) [[Morane-Saulnier M.S.406]] fighter aircraft. Ihlefeld was credited with shooting one of them down at 20:15, the other Morane was credited to ''[[Hauptmann]]'' (Captain) Hanns Trübenbach.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=304}} On 30 June 1940, he was credited with two victories over [[Bristol Blenheim]] light bombers shot down at 12:45 and 15:30, his second and third of the war.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=327}} Although Ihlefeld was unhurt, damage to his Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;E sustained in one of these encounters, resulted in a [[forced landing]] near [[Saint-Omer]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=329}}

Ihlefeld received an early promotion to ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' (first lieutenant) on 1 June 1940 followed by his appointment to ''[[Staffelkapitän]]'' (squadron leader) of 2 ''Staffel'' in I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2.{{refn|According to Prien, the appointment to ''[[Staffelkapitän]]'' (squadron leader) of 2 ''Staffel'' of I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 occurred sometime in June 1940.{{sfn|Prien|1995|p=2372}} According to Obermaier, this happened on 1 July 1940.{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=31}}|group="Note"}} He was awarded the Iron Cross 1st Class ({{lang|de|Eisernes Kreuz erster Klasse}}) on 4 July 1940.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}} On 9 July 1940, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was tasked with flying [[escort fighter]] missions for [[Kampfgeschwader 2|''Kampfgeschwader'' 2]] (KG&nbsp;2—2nd Bomber Wing) attacking British shipping in the [[English Channel]]. These types of missions were referred to as ''[[Kanalkampf]]'' by the Germans and resulted in a series of air battles between the ''Luftwaffe'' and the British [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF). On the third mission of the day (16:25&nbsp;– 17:20), escorting a flight of [[Dornier Do 17]] bombers to their targets, Ihlefeld claimed his fourth victory of the war, a [[Hawker Hurricane]] fighter aircraft shot down at 16:30.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=334}}

===Battle of Britain and Channel Front===
On 10 July 1940, seven RAF bombers attacked the [[Amiens – Glisy Aerodrome]], all of which were shot down by the ''Luftwaffe''. On this day, 47 Do&nbsp;17 bombers from I. and III. ''Gruppe'' of KG&nbsp;2, supported by one [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]] [[heavy fighter]] and two single-engined fighter ''Gruppen'' attacked British shipping in the English Channel. In the resulting aerial combat, ''Luftwaffe'' pilots initially claimed 23 victories, 10 of these were later confirmed by the ''Luftwaffe''. Actual RAF losses that day were three aircraft shot down, further seven made forced landings and were severely damaged. RAF pilots claimed the destruction of 16 German aircraft, actual losses were four Do&nbsp;17s and three Bf&nbsp;110s shot down plus further four damaged aircraft. These events marked the beginning of the [[Battle of Britain]] (10 July&nbsp;– 31 October 1940).{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=335}}

On 11 July 1940, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was ordered to relocate to [[Jever]] in northern Germany. In the following four weeks, the Gruppe received a period of rest and the aircraft were given a maintenance overhaul prior to moving back to the Channel Front, to an airfield at [[Marck, Pas-de-Calais|Marck]], east of [[Calais]], on 8 August.{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=336, 343}} [[Adolf Hitler]] had issued [[Führer Directives|Führer Directive]] no. 17 (''Weisung Nr.'' 17) on 1 August 1940; the strategic objective was to engage and defeat the RAF so as to achieve [[air superiority]] in preparation for [[Operation Sea Lion]] (''Unternehmen Seelöwe''), the proposed amphibious invasion of Great Britain.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=338}} On 13 August 1940, during [[Operation Eagle Attack]] (code name ''[[Adlertag]]''), I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was tasked with providing fighter escort for [[Junkers Ju 87]] [[dive bomber]]s from IV. ''Gruppe'' of [[Lehrgeschwader 1|''Lehrgeschwader'' 1]] (LG&nbsp;1—1st Demonstration Wing) and II. ''Gruppe'' of [[Sturzkampfgeschwader 1|''Sturzkampfgeschwader'' 1]] (StG&nbsp;1—1st Dive Bomber Wing), destined to attack the RAF airfields at [[London Southend Airport|Rochford]] and [[RAF Detling|Detling]]. During this mission (16:25&nbsp;– 17:35),<ref group=Note>All times used in this section are [[Central European Time]] unless otherwise noted.</ref> Ihlefeld claimed his fifth victory, a Hurricane.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=347}} British losses from 16:15 to 16:36 [[GMT]] amounted to one Hurricane from [[No. 43 Squadron RAF|No. 43 Squadron]] whose pilot, [[Pilot Officer]] C.A Woods-Scawen [[Parachute|bailed out]] unhurt. Four Hurricanes from [[No. 56 Squadron RAF|No. 56 Squadron]] were lost—Pilot Officer C.C.O Joubert was slightly wounded, [[Flying Officer]] P.F.Mc Davies was badly burned, Flying Officer R.E.P Brooker bailed out unhurt while [[Sergeant]] P. Hillwood bailed out and swam {{Convert|2.5|mi|km|abbr=off|sp=us}} to shore. The first two men were shot down over Rochfort.{{sfn|Mason|1969|pp=240–241}}

On 22 August 1940, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew a combat air patrol over [[Southern England]]. Taking his total to seven victories, Ihlefeld had claimed two [[Supermarine Spitfire]] fighters shot down in the vicinity of [[Dover]]. Five Spitfires were lost by [[Fighter Command]] on this day.{{sfn|Mason|1969|p=292}} Weather conditions improved over Southern England on 24 August 1940 and I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was ordered to fly a combat air patrol over [[Kent]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=357}} The ''Gruppe'' flew three missions that day and claimed ten aerial victories, all of which over Spitfires, two of which were credited to Ihlefeld. Ihlefeld's first victory was claimed at 12:30 and the second at 17:00.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=359}} Fighter Command lost five Spitfires and one damaged on 24 August. Two losses roughly match Ihlefeld's claim. [[No. 54 Squadron RAF|No. 54 Squadron]] lost one; Pilot Officer C. Stewart bailed out in the afternoon, the time unknown. Pilot Officer D. Mc Gray was shot down at 11:15 GMT and bailed out of the [[No. 610 Squadron RAF|No. 610 Squadron]] Spitfire ''X4067''. Both men were shot down near Dover.{{sfn|Mason|1969|pp=298–299}}

On 30 August 1940, Ihlefeld claimed his tenth victory of the war, another Spitfire probably shot down over the English Channel near Calais. On this day, ''[[Gruppenkommandeur]]'' (group commander) of I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2, ''Hauptmann'' Bernhard Mielke, was [[killed in action]]. Later that day, Ihlefeld was appointed his successor as ''Gruppenkommandeur''.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=363}} The next day, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew fighter escort missions for II.(S)/LG&nbsp;2, the ground attack ''Gruppe'' of LG&nbsp;2. On two separate missions they attacked the airfield at [[London Biggin Hill Airport|Biggin Hill]] on their first mission (10:25&nbsp;– 11:20), and in the evening [[Croydon Airport|Croydon]] airfield. The German flight believed they encountered Hurricanes from [[No. 303 Polish Fighter Squadron]] on the second mission. The Germans claimed four victories, one of which by Ihlefeld, for the loss of two in combat.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=368}} 303 Squadron, if engaged during this day, suffered no fighters damaged or destroyed on this day. Their likely opponents were from [[No. 17 Squadron RAF|No. 17 Squadron]] which lost one Hurricane. The pilot Sergeant G.A Steward was unhurt. I./LG&nbsp;2 lost one Bf&nbsp;109 destroyed and one sixty percent damaged. ''Oberleutnant'' von Perthes was shot down and killed by Flying Officer T. Bird-Wilson.{{sfn|Mason|1969|p=331}}

On 2 September 1940, he increased his total to 13 aerial victories, claiming two Spitfires, on a mission against the [[RAF Hornchurch|Hornchurch]] airfield.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=373}} No Spitfires were lost in the battle over Hornchrch though two Spitfires belonging to [[No. 222 Squadron RAF|No. 222 Squadron]] were damaged.{{sfn|Mason|1969|p=340}} Three day later, Detling airfield was the target, and Ihlefeld again claimed two Spitfires shot down.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=374}} On 6 September, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 escorted [[Schnellkampfgeschwader 210|''Erprobungsgruppe'' 210]] to various airfields in the greater London area. Again Ihlefeld claimed two victories, two Hurricanes shot down took his total to 17 aerial victories.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=377}} 19 Hurricanes were destroyed to all causes and two damaged on this date in intensive air battles.{{sfn|Mason|1969|pp=355–356}}

[[File:Heinkel over Wapping.jpg|thumb|left|[[Heinkel He 111]] bomber over the [[Surrey Commercial Docks|Surrey docks]] and [[Wapping]] in the East End of London on 7 September 1940]]
On 7 September 1940, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 participated in [[The Blitz#Loge and Seeschlange|Operation "Loge"]], 350 bombers escorted by 648 fighters, attacked various targets in the greater London area. Ihlefeld's ''Gruppe'' protected those bombers heading for the [[Dock (maritime)|docks]] in the [[East End of London]]. On this mission, Ihlefeld claimed a Hurricane shot down at 18:05 and another one at 18:10.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=382}} 17 Hurricanes were destroyed and 7 damaged this day. Up to 19 of these aircraft were hit or destroyed in the time-frame of the claim.{{sfn|Mason|1969|pp=365–366}} The ''Luftwaffe'' flew another large scale attack on 11 September. In total, 280 bombers, 96 of which headed for London, supported by 750 fighter aircraft, headed for England. Ihlefeld claimed a Spitfire destroyed at 17:05 and a Hurricane at 17:10 that day.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=385}} This took his total to 21 aerial victories in World War II, for which he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] ({{lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes}}) on 13 September 1940. The presentation was made by Hitler personally on 16 September 1940.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}} One day before the presentation, the [[Battle of Britain Day]], Ihlefeld had claimed the 22nd aerial victory, a Hurricane.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=387}} At 10:00 on 24 September 1940, Ihlefeld engaged Spitfire's in combat over [[Maidstone]], claiming one shot down.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=394}} There were four Spitfires lost and two damaged in combat on this date. None were shot down at the time of the claim or in this district.{{sfn|Mason|1969|p=410}} Three days later, on a fighter escort to mission to London, he claimed two Hurricanes, taking his total to 25 aerial victories. On this mission, Ihlefeld lost his 1. ''Staffel'' commander, ''Oberleutnant'' Adolf Buhl.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=396}} Responsible for his loss was ''[[Fähnrich]]'' (Officer Candidate) [[Hans-Joachim Marseille]] who had abandoned Buhl. Ihlefeld was forced to give Marseille a stern rebuke for his conduct in combat and eventually dismissed Marseille from LG&nbsp;2.{{sfn|Heaton|Lewis|2012|pp=18–20}} He was promoted to ''Hauptmann'' on 1 October 1940.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}}

The war of attrition against the RAF had cost I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 dearly, and the entire ''Gruppe'' had to be moved back to the home airfield [[Cologne Butzweilerhof Airport|Köln-Butzweilerhof]] to reform and re-equip on 5 November 1940. From 30 June to end of October 1940, the ''Gruppe'' had claimed 92 aerial victories for the loss of 10 pilots either killed or missing in action, further 4 pilots had been taken prisoner of war. In the same timeframe, 38 aircraft were damaged or lost.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=420}} I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was ordered back to the Channel Front on 26 December 1940. That day, it flew to the airfield at Calais-Marck and was subordinated to the [[Stab (Luftwaffe designation)|''Stab'']] (headquarters unit) of [[Jagdgeschwader 52|''Jagdgeschwader'' 52]] (JG&nbsp;52—52nd Fighter Wing).{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=450}} Ihlefeld claimed his 26th victory of the war at 15:50 on 17 January 1941 northwest of [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=457}}

On 5 February 1941, the RAF began the [[Circus offensive]] against the ''Luftwaffe'', a series of attacks flown by heavily escorted bombers targeted the coastal region in northern France. Ihlefeld claimed a Spitfire destroyed at 17:35 on 10 February. The RAF had sent a Circus against various targets in the vicinity of [[Pas-de-Calais]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=460, 462–463}} Four days later, he claimed two Spitfires shot down on a combat air patrol over [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford]] and [[Canterbury]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=467}} On 26 February 1941, Ihlefeld shot down Sergeant Howard Squire, his 30th victory of the war, in his Spitfire from No. 54 Squadron on Circus No.&nbsp;5 mission.{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=471–472}} Twelve Blenheim bombers from [[No. 139 Squadron RAF|No. 139 Squadron]] had targeted harbor installations at Calais. They were protected by Hurricane and Spitfire fighters from No. 54, [[No. 74 Squadron RAF|No. 74]], [[No. 92 Squadron RAF|No. 92]], [[No. 601 Squadron RAF|No. 601]] and [[No. 609 Squadron RAF|No. 609 Squadron]]. Squire made a forced landing and was taken [[prisoner of war]].{{sfn|Price|2012|loc=chptr. 18 "Act of Chivalry"}} In combat with Spitfires west of Calais, Ihlefeld claimed his 31st victory at 17:20 on 1 March 1941.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=471}} At 15:45 on 13 March 1941, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 combated Spitfires {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=off|sp=us}} north of [[Cap Gris Nez]] and Ihlefeld again claimed one of his opponents shot down.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=475}} His next two claims were submitted following combat over [[Hastings]] on 19 March. Two Spitfires shot down at 19:08 and 19:10 took his tally to 34 aerial victories.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=477}} Ihlefeld claimed his last victory on the Channel Front on 25 March 1941. The combat with another Spitfire took place in the vicinity of [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]]. On 30 March 1941, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was ordered to relocate to [[Vienna]].{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=480}} At the Channel Front since December 1940, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 had claimed 24 aerial victories for the loss of 3 pilots killed.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=481}}

===Balkan Campaign===
The [[Balkan Campaign (World War II)|Balkan Campaign]] began on 6 April 1941, with multiple objectives. [[Operation Marita]] was the codename for the German invasion of Greece, while I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was committed to the [[invasion of Yugoslavia]]. Based at [[Radomir (town)|Radomir]] in Bulgaria, the unit was subordinated to ''[[Generaloberst]]'' (Colonel General) [[Wolfram Freiherr von Richthofen]]'s [[8th Air Corps (Germany)|VIII. ''Fliegerkorps'']] (8th Air Corps).{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=488}} I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 primary targets in this campaign were various ''[[Yugoslav Royal Air Force|Jugoslovensko Kraljevsko Ratno Vazduhoplovstvo]]'' (JKRV—Yugoslav Royal Air Force) airfields in the greater [[Skopje]] area. The ''Gruppe'', together with the ground attack unit II.(S)/LG&nbsp;2, flew five combat missions on the first day of the campaign. During one of these missions, [[strafing]] the railway up the [[Vardar]] valley and an airfield near [[Niš]], Ihlefeld was shot down in his Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;E-7 (''Werknummer'' 2057—factory number) by [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft artillery]] and was captured by Yugoslavian soldiers.{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=496, 498}}{{refn|1=According to Ciglic, Weal and Savic, Ihlefeld shot down a JKRV [[Potez 25]] on the landing approach, Shortly after, he was hit by a lucky shot fired from the ground by Serbian kap Vlastimir Belic, forcing him to [[Parachute|bail out]] near [[Donji Dušnik]].{{sfn|Ciglic|Weal|Savic|2013|p=27}}|group="Note"}} The airfield at Niš was practically deserted and Ihlefeld had been hit by small arms fire and was slightly wounded in the head.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=194}} While in their custody, he was allegedly severely beaten, and threatened with execution by firing squad. On 14 April 1941, he was rescued by German troops of the [[5th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|5th Panzer Division]] after eight days in captivity, and returned to Germany to recover.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=122}}{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=498, 514}}

The invasion of Yugoslavia ended when an armistice was signed on 17 April 1941.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=522}} That day, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 relocated to [[Ptolemaida]], Greece and to [[Larissa]] three days later.{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=523, 531}} On 21 April, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew missions against the port of [[Piraeus]] and [[Athens]] .{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=533}} I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 then moved to [[Eleusis]] on 27 April.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=547}} The [[Battle of Greece]] ended on 30 April 1941 and the ''Gruppe'' was granted a period of rest which ended on 2 May 1941.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=551}} In preparation for the [[Battle of Crete]] (20 May&nbsp;– 1 June 1941), I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew reconnaissance missions over Crete on 13 May 1941.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=566}} Missions against Crete were flown from an airfield at [[Molaoi]].{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=338}} One day later, the unit flew its first ground attack mission against various targets.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=566}} On 22 May 1941, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 successfully attacked {{HMS|Fiji|58|6}} off of Crete, damaging her severely.{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=566}} Ihlefeld was credited with his only aerial victory over Crete on 26 May 1941. His 36th victory was claimed over [[Maleme]] against a Hurricane fighter.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=383}}{{sfn|Prien|1992|p=606}} Actions over Crete ended for I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 on 31 May 1941. By this date, the ''Gruppe'' had claimed six aerial victories in this campaign. I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was then withdrawn and relocated to [[Belgrad]] in preparation for [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Prien|1992|pp=614, 616}}

===Eastern Front===
On 18 June 1941, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 was moved to [[Bucharest]] and placed under the command of JG&nbsp;77. The ''Geschwader'' was located in the sector of [[Army Group South|''Heeresgruppe Süd'']] (Army Group South).{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=628}} Three days later, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 moved to [[Roman, Bulgaria|Roman]].{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=630}} That evening, the pilots and ground crews were briefed of the upcoming invasion of the Soviet Union, which opened the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=632}} At 3:20 on 22 June 1941, 70 Bf&nbsp;109s of JG&nbsp;77 and I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 crossed into Soviet airspace and attacked airfields and provided fighter protection for III. ''Gruppe'' of [[Kampfgeschwader 27|''Kampfgeschwader'' 27]] (KG&nbsp;27—27th Bomber Wing).{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=635}} Ihlefeld claimed his first two victories, both SB-2 bombers, on the Eastern Front on 23 June 1941. JG&nbsp;77 and I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew seven combat missions that day. On the first mission of the day, 34 Bf&nbsp;109 provided fighter escort for two ''Gruppen'' of KG&nbsp;27 in support of the advancing German ground forces. At 5:50, Ihlefeld claimed his 37th victory of the war.{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=628}} On the seventh mission, which began at 19:10, he claimed the second bomber in the area of [[Chernivtsi]].{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=644}} Two [[Ilyushin DB-3]] bombers shot down on 26 June 1941 took his total to 40 aerial victories in World War II.{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=651}} This achievement earned him the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]] ({{Lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub}}) on 27 June 1941. He was the 16th member of the German armed forces to be so honored.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=123}} That day, he was also mentioned in the ''[[Wehrmachtbericht]]'' radio report, the first of six such mentions.{{sfn|The Wehrmacht Reports 1939–1945 Volume 1|p=591}}

Ihlefeld, on a combat air patrol in the vicinity of [[Iași]], claimed a I-16 fighter aircraft shot down on 28 June.{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=654}} The next day I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 moved to an airfield at [[Uzhhorod]] and to [[Tudora, Ștefan Vodă|Tudora]] on 1 July 1941.{{sfn|Prien|1993|pp=657, 660}} On 2 July, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew five combat missions and Ihlefeld achieved his 42nd aerial victory over a [[Polikarpov I-153]] biplane fighter.{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=663}} On a Stuka escort mission to [[Kamianets-Podilskyi]] on 4 July, he shot down a I-15.{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=666}} On 6 July, I.(J)/LG&nbsp;2 flew seven combat missions, on two of which they had enemy contact. On the sixth mission of the day, the unit encountered five SB-2 bombers escorted by seven I-16 fighters. In the resulting aerial combat, Ihlefeld shot down one I-16, his 44th victory.{{sfn|Prien|1993|pp=669–670}}

On 30 August 1941 he became an "[[Aviators who became ace in a day|ace-in-a-day]]" by shooting down five Soviet aircraft, his 48th to 52nd aerial victories.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=123}}
In the spring of 1942, a series of multiple victories (five aircraft on 24 March, seven on 30 March and seven on 20 April), saw Ihlefeld become the fifth pilot on 22 April 1942 to reach 100 victories during World War II.{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=243}} During the period of Ihlefeld's leadership, ''I./JG 77'' was credited with the destruction of 323 enemy aircraft while losing only 17 [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]s.

===Wing Commander===
On 10 May 1942, Ihlefeld was replaced by ''Hauptmann'' [[Heinrich Bär]] as ''Gruppenkommandeur'' of I. ''Gruppe''. Ihlefeld had been selected to take over JG&nbsp;52 as ''[[Geschwaderkommodore]]'' (Wing Commander). Prior to this appointment, he was sent to the ''Geschwaderstab'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 51|''Jagdgeschwader'' 51]] (JG&nbsp;51—51st Fighter Wing) as a commander-in-training under ''Hauptmann'' [[Karl-Gottfried Nordmann]].{{sfn|Prien|1993|p=999}} In June 1942, Ihlefeld was promoted to ''[[Major (Germany)|Major]]'' (major) and on 26 June took command of JG&nbsp;52.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=123}} On 22 July 1942, whilst flying over the front in his [[Fieseler Fi 156|Fieseler Fi&nbsp;156 ''Storch'']], a small [[liaison aircraft]], he was shot down and badly wounded by Soviet fighters,{{sfn|Hayward|1998|p=146}} this took him out of the front line until July 1943, when he joined the newly formed [[Jagdgeschwader 25|''Jagdgeschwader'' 25]] (JG&nbsp;25—25th Fighter Wing) as ''Geschwaderkommodore'', leading the group's high-altitude Bf 109s in ultimately unsuccessful operations against RAF [[de Havilland Mosquito]]s, and later [[United States Air Force]] (USAAF) heavy bomber formations in [[defense of the Reich]] missions.

On 1 February 1944, Ihlefeld was promoted to ''[[Oberstleutnant]]'' (lieutenant colonel).{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=124}} In May 1944, he briefly became ''Geschwaderkommodore'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 11|''Jagdgeschwader'' 11]] (JG&nbsp;11—11th Fighter Wing), before taking command of [[Jagdgeschwader 1 (World War 2)|''Jagdgeschwader'' 1]] "Oesau" (JG&nbsp;1—1st Fighter Wing) on 20 May 1944. Ihlefeld replaced Bär as ''Geschwaderkommodore'' who had led the ''Geschwader'' since the death in combat of ''Oberst'' [[Walter Oesau]] on 11 May 1944.{{sfn|Mombeek|1992|pp=232–233}} On 14 July 1944, Ihlefeld claimed a [[North American P-51 Mustang]] and a Spitfire shot down.{{sfn|Mombeek|1992|p=251}} He was credited with his next victories on 25 July, claiming the destruction of a [[Avro Lancaster]] [[heavy bomber]] and a Spitfire.{{sfn|Mombeek|1992|p=252}}

===Operation Bodenplatte and end of war===
Ihlefeld participated and led JG&nbsp;1 in [[Operation Bodenplatte]], the failed attempt to cripple [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] air forces in the Low Countries. The objective of Bodenplatte was to gain air superiority during the stagnant stage of the [[Battle of the Bulge]] and dates back to meeting held on 16 September 1944. That day, Hitler informed ''[[General der Flieger]]'' (Lieutenant General) [[Werner Kreipe]], acting Chief of the [[General Staff]] of the ''Luftwaffe'', about the planned offensive.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=1}} Ihlefeld probably learned of this operation on 5 December 1944.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=12}} ''[[Luftwaffenkommando West]]'' (Air Command West) had ordered every wing commander of all the ''[[Jagdgeschwader]]s'' destined to participate in the operation to attend a meeting at the headquarters of [[2nd Fighter Corps (Germany)|II. ''Jagdkorps'']] (2nd Fighter Corps) at [[Flammersfeld]] near [[Koblenz]].{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=2}} At the time, Ihlefeld was faced with a very challenging leadership situation. Prior to the operation, JG&nbsp;1 had lost the commander of I. ''Gruppe'', ''Hauptmann'' [[Hans Ehlers]] who was killed in action on 27 December, and the commander of III. ''Gruppe'', ''Hauptmann'' [[Erich Woitke]] who had been killed in action on 24 December. The commander of II. ''Gruppe'', ''Hauptmann'' [[Hermann Staiger]], had landed his combat damaged aircraft at Frankfurt and had not yet returned to his unit.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=12}} On the early afternoon of 31 December 1944, Ihlefeld summoned his three new ''Gruppenkommandeure'' to [[Twente]] for the mission briefing. The new I. ''Gruppe'' commander was ''Hauptmann'' Georg Hackbarth, II. ''Gruppe'' was led by ''Oberleutnant'' Fritz Wegner and III. ''Gruppe'' was now headed by ''Hauptmann'' Harald Moldenhauer.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=13}}

On 1 January 1945, the ''Geschwaderstab'' and I. ''Gruppe'', both based at Twente, took off at 8:10 and joined up with and III. ''Gruppe'', based at [[Rheine-Bentlage Air Base|Rheine]], which had taken off at 8:15. Their designated targets were the airfields at [[Maldegem]] and [[Ursel Airfield|Ursel]]. The formation was led by four [[Junkers Ju 88]] [[night fighter]]s from [[Nachtjagdgeschwader 1|''Nachtjagdgeschwader'' 1]] (NJG&nbsp;1—1st Night Fighter Wing); they were the pathfinders for the single-engined fighters.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=5}} The formation of 20 [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190|Focke&nbsp;Wulf Fw&nbsp;190&nbsp;A-8]]s and 30 Bf&nbsp;109&nbsp;G-14s, flying at an altitude of {{Convert|50|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}, headed west. As the flight approached [[The Hague]], they came under heavy and precise German anti-artillery fire. The German anti-artillery units had not been informed of the ''Luftwaffe'' operation. Several aircraft were hit, including the aircraft of Ihlefeld who had to make a forced landing near [[Rotterdam]]. II. ''Gruppe'', based at Drope, between [[Lengerich, Lower Saxony|Lengerich]] and [[Bawinkel]], had also taken off at 8:15 and headed for the airfield at [[Ghent]]/Sint-Denijs-Westrem. ( Polish Fighter Wing No 131, Sq 301/308/317 Spitfire IX/XVI ){{sfn|Mombeek|1992|p=290}}{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=19}} JG&nbsp;1 continued with their mission without Ihlefeld leading the decisive phase of the attack. The result of the attack can be described as [[Pyrrhic victory]] at best. JG&nbsp;1 claimed the destruction of around 60 enemy aircraft, of which 54 were destroyed on the ground, for the loss of 25 pilots and 29 aircraft.{{sfn|Manrho|Pütz|2010|p=39}}

[[File:Heinkel He 162 in France 1945.jpg|thumb|right|He&nbsp;162&nbsp;A-2 (''Werknummer'' 120230) in France, brought to the USA by [[Operation Lusty]]]]
Following of Operation Bodenplatte, and failing to maintain air superiority over the Ardennes area, a severely weakened II. ''Gruppe'' transferred to [[Insterburg]] in [[East Prussia]], present-day [[Chernyakhovsk]] in Russia. I. ''Gruppe'' faced RAF fighters over [[Hengelo|Hengelo-Twente]] on 14 January 1945. JG&nbsp;1 lost 12 pilots with 7 being killed, 3 wounded and 2 missing. Spitfires shot down the entire 1. and 2. ''Staffeln'' of JG&nbsp;1 at [[Enschede Airport Twente|Twente airport]] as they took off, for the loss of two. Ihlefeld threatened to [[court martial]] ''Major'' Günther Capito, the new commander of I. ''Gruppe'', for such a disastrous loss but was unable to during the transferring to the Eastern Front. In Poland JG&nbsp;1 were briefly assigned to ''[[Luftflotte Reich]]'' (Air Fleet Reich).

He was promoted to ''[[Oberst]]'' (colonel) on 30 January 1945.{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=124}} Late in the war, elements of the ''Geschwader'' were equipped with the [[Heinkel He 162|He 162 ''Volksjäger'']], a single-engine, jet-powered fighter aircraft. He&nbsp;162&nbsp;A-2 (''Werknummer'' 120230), Ihlefeld flew this aircraft during the war, is currently in possession of the [[National Air and Space Museum]] collection.{{sfn|Skaarup|2009|p=248}}

==Later life==
In 1984, Winston Ramsey, the editor of ''[[After the Battle]]'' magazine, contacted both Ihlefeld and Squire, who Ihlefeld had shot down on 26 February 1941, and arranged a meeting. Subsequently, Ihlefeld and Squire met at Calais.{{sfn|Price|2012|loc=chptr. 18 "Act of Chivalry"}} Ihlefeld died on 8 August 1995 in [[Wennigsen]], [[Lower Saxony]]. His ashes were buried on the [[urn]] field near the chapel on the old cemetery in [[Kirchheim unter Teck]], [[Baden-Württemberg]].{{sfn|Stockert|1996|p=124}}

==Summary of career==

===Aerial victory claims===
Matthews and Foreman, authors of ''Luftwaffe Aces — Biographies and Victory Claims'', researched the [[German Federal Archives]] and found documentation for 122 aerial victory claims, plus five further unconfirmed claims. This number includes nine claims during the Spanish Civil War, 48 on the Western Front, including three four-engined bombers, and 65 on the Eastern Front.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|pp=570–572}}

Victory claims were logged to a map-reference (PQ = ''Planquadrat''), for example "PQ 05 Ost S/ET-1". The ''Luftwaffe'' grid map ({{lang|de|Jägermeldenetz}}) covered all of Europe, western Russia and North Africa and was composed of rectangles measuring 15 [[Minute of arc|minutes]] of [[latitude]] by 30 minutes of [[longitude]], an area of about {{Convert|360|sqmi|sqkm}}. These sectors were then subdivided into 36 smaller units to give a location area 3 × 4&nbsp;km in size.{{sfn|''Planquadrat''}}

