| {{flag|Japan}}
| [[Tokyo]]
| {{sort|2017-08-30|30 August – 1 September}}
| May traveled to Japan to improve relations with the country and discuss a potential new UK-Japan trade agreement for the period after [[Brexit]] concludes.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-japan-visit-brexit-trade-british-business-leave-eu-uk-north-korea-a7919456.html</ref>  Her visit also involved discussions surrounding threats which [[List of North Korean missile tests|North Korea's nuclear missile tests]] posed to Japan.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41088404</ref>  She met with, among others, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/31/theresa-may-is-in-japan-to-talk-trade-but-she-cant-give-tokyo-what-it-really-wants.html</ref> and Emperor Akihito.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41122792</ref> During a joint press conference in Tokyo, Abe and May pledged agreement to a new economic deal between both Britain and Japan, as well as British and Japanese companies, which would in the future expand on the current EU-Japan deal following the completion of Brexit.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/aug/31/theresa-may-secures-japanese-pledge-on-post-brexit-trade-deal</ref><ref>https://www.ft.com/content/594db41e-8f18-11e7-a352-e46f43c5825d</ref>
|-
|{{flag|Canada}}
|[[Ottawa]]
| {{sort|2017-09-18|18 September}}
|May traveled to Canada on her first ever visit to the country to meet with Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] to further deepen the strong bond between the two countries, where they discussed issues of mutual interest, including innovation, security, climate change, China, Islamaphobia, trade and advancing gender equality.<ref>http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/news/2017/9/18/top-canada-stories--fentanyl-from-china--islamophobia--more.html</ref><ref>http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/UK-Prime-Minister-Theresa-May-to-visit-Canada-547824</ref>  May and Trudeau later held a joint press conference as well.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2017/sep/18/boris-johnson-brexit-theresa-may-trudeau-conservatives-split-over-boris-johnsons-brexit-article-as-backlash-continues-politics-live</ref>  May also showed solidarity with Canada and [[Bombardier Aerospace|Bombardier]] over their dispute with [[Boeing]] as Bombardier have a factory in [[Northern Ireland]] and expressed optimism for Trudeau's promise of a "seamless" transition concerning UK-Canadian trade relations following the completion of Brexit.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/justin-trudeau-theresa-may-canada-brexit-trade-deal-ceta-ottawa-a7954366.html</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41301926</ref>
|-
| {{flagu|United States}} 
| [[New York City]] 
| {{sort|2017-09-19|19–20 September}}
| May travelled from Canada to New York to attend the [[United Nations General Assembly|UN General Assembly]] alongside the British foreign secretary, [[Boris Johnson]], though it was later announced that Johnson's separate UN meeting was cancelled and that he would fly back with May.<ref>http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/national/15547309.Where___s_the_emergency_Brexit__PM_and_Boris_share_plane_home_from_UN_gathering/</ref> It will be the second speech May makes to the UN.  After arriving in New York, May held a press conference about Brexit and her relationship with Johnson<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-theresa-may-speech-latest-florence-boris-johnson-rebellion-contribution-a7955961.html</ref> and also held a special meeting with President Trump's daughter [[Ivanka Trump|Ivanka]] and United Nations Secretary General [[Antonio Guterres]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/20/ivanka-trump-praises-theresa-may-meet-new-york/</ref>  

On September 20, May held a bilateral meeting  on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly with Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] and Rouhani announced that Iran was ready to expand ties to Britain in all fields,<ref name=iranmay>http://ifpnews.com/exclusive/iran-uk-expansion-bilateral-ties/</ref> citing Britain's support of the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]].<ref name=iranmay />  She also attended a major UN Security Council meeting which saw the passage of a UN resolution on peacekeeping reforms and met with US Vice President [[Mike Pence]].<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/pence-applauds-un-resolution-on-peacekeeping-reform/2017/09/20/1f13bcdc-9e2f-11e7-b2a7-bc70b6f98089_story.html</ref>  May would later address the [[United Nations General Assembly|UN General Assembly]] and warned tech firms to go "further and faster" in removing extremist content promoting terrorism,<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41327816</ref> as well as other issues.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/trump-theresa-may-paris-agreement-criticism-climate-deal-un-speech-a7958096.html</ref><ref>http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/856711/theresa-may-united-nations-millions-withhold-terrorism-bureaucracy</ref>  She also met with US President [[Donald Trump]] on the General Assembly sidelines to discuss trade, security, defense and foreign relations between Britain and the United States of America.<ref>http://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/The-Latest-Kerry-charges-Trump-speech-to-UN-was-12214303.php</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d7kdI0tCnV4</ref>
|-
| {{flagu|Italy}}
| [[Florence]]
| {{sort|2017-09-22|22 September}}
| May visited Florence to give a landmark speech on [[Brexit]].<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/theresa-may-vows-to-protect-britains-eu-nationals-in-landmark-brexit-speech-a3641456.html</ref> She claimed to want a transitional period after Britain's exit from the EU, to allow time to discuss a trade deal, whilst still paying money into the EU budget. May also announced that the UK will "honour its [financial] commitments" so as to not make other EU countries pay more or receive less during the current EU budget period.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Robert|title=Five key points from Theresa May’s speech|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9b183886-9faf-11e7-8cd4-932067fbf946|website=Financial Times|accessdate=24 September 2017|date=22 September 2017}}</ref>
