[[File:Saijō Sake Matsuri 2017.jpg|thumb|Saijō Sake Matsuri]] The {{Nihongo|'''Saijō Sake Festival'''|西条酒まつり|Saijō Sake Matsuri}} is a [[sake]] (rice wine) [[matsuri]] festival held annually in [[Saijō, Hiroshima (Kamo)|Saijō]] [[Higashihiroshima]], [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], [[Japan]].<ref>https://en.japantravel.com/hiroshima/saijo-sake-festival/2891</ref>
Saijō is famed for local sake or {{ill|Saijō Sake|ja|西条酒}}.<ref>http://visithiroshima.net/things_to_do/seasonal_events/autumn/sake_festival.html</ref> Within the narrow streets of the Sakagura Dori ("Sake Storehouse Road") area near JR [[Saijō Station]] are the [[Namako wall]] (white-lattice walled) and {{ill|Sekishu Gawara|ja|石州瓦}} (red-roof tile) roofs of ten well-known sake breweries; Chiyonoharu, Fukubijin, Hakubotan, Kamoki, Kamoizumi, Kamotsuru, Kirei, Saijotsuru, Sakurafubuki, and Sanyotsuru.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ar.jal.com/world/en/guidetojapan/detail/index.html?spot_code=sakematsuri |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-10-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006211558/https://www.ar.jal.com/world/en/guidetojapan/detail/index.html?spot_code=sakematsuri |archivedate=2017-10-06 |df= }}</ref> In July 1995, Saijō was made the home of the Brewery Laboratory of the National Tax Office.
The Saijō Sake Matsuri is an important part of [[Hiroshima]] culture, which draws crowds of between 100,000–200,000 revelers and sake connoisseurs each October before the brewing season (October–March) begins.<ref>https://sakematsuri.com/</ref> Visitors also enjoy numerous attractions, sidestalls and games. There is also a wide variety of traditional as well as modern carnival food available.<ref>http://gethiroshima.com/event/saijo-sake-matsuri/</ref>
